# Set seed for reproducibility
set.seed(123)

# Define the number of employees
n <- 200

# Generate Gender with a 70% Male and 30% Female ratio
gender <- sample(c("Male", "Female"), n, replace = TRUE, prob = c(0.7, 0.3))

# Generate Ethnicity with biases: 60% White, 15% Asian, 15% Black, 10% Other
ethnicity <- sample(c("White", "Asian", "Black", "Other"), n, replace = TRUE, prob = c(0.6, 0.15, 0.15, 0.1))

# Generate Age: normally distributed around 35 years with a standard deviation of 10
age <- round(rnorm(n, mean = 35, sd = 10))

# Generate Experience: normally distributed around 10 years with a standard deviation of 5
experience <- round(rnorm(n, mean = 10, sd = 5))

# Generate Job Level: 40% Junior, 40% Mid, 20% Senior
job_level <- sample(c("Junior", "Mid", "Senior"), n, replace = TRUE, prob = c(0.4, 0.4, 0.2))

# Generate Department: 50% Finance, 30% IT, 20% HR
department <- sample(c("Finance", "IT", "HR"), n, replace = TRUE, prob = c(0.5, 0.3, 0.2))

# Generate Salary: normally distributed with mean depending on job level
salary <- ifelse(job_level == "Junior", 
                 round(rnorm(n, mean = 50000, sd = 10000)),
                 ifelse(job_level == "Mid",
                        round(rnorm(n, mean = 80000, sd = 15000)),
                        round(rnorm(n, mean = 120000, sd = 20000))))

# Add Turnover status: 20% left (Turnover = 1) and 80% stayed (Turnover = 0)
turnover <- sample(c(0, 1), n, replace = TRUE, prob = c(0.8, 0.2))

# Add Performance Score: normally distributed around 70 with a standard deviation of 10
performance_score <- round(rnorm(n, mean = 70, sd = 10))

# Generate Tenure: uniformly distributed between 0 and 30 years
tenure <- round(runif(n, min = 0, max = 30))

# Generate the dataframe
employee_data <- data.frame(
  EmployeeID = 1:n,
  Gender = gender,
  Ethnicity = ethnicity,
  Age = age,
  Experience = experience,
  JobLevel = job_level,
  Department = department,
  Salary = salary,
  Turnover = turnover,
  PerformanceScore = performance_score,
  Tenure = tenure
)

#PREDICTIVE ANALYSIS#

# Fit logistic regression model to predict turnover
turnover_model <- glm(Turnover ~ Gender + Age + JobLevel + Department + Ethnicity + PerformanceScore + Tenure, data = employee_data, family = binomial)

# Predict probabilities of turnover
employee_data$TurnoverProb <- predict(turnover_model, type = "response")

# Summarize turnover probabilities by categories including tenure
summary_data <- employee_data %>%
  group_by(Gender, JobLevel, Department, Ethnicity, Tenure) %>%
  summarise(AverageTurnoverProb = mean(TurnoverProb), .groups = 'drop')

# Create the summary string
summary_string <- paste("Gender: 70% Male, 30% Female\n",
                        "Ethnicity: 60% White, 15% Asian, 15% Black, 10% Other\n",
                        "Job Levels: 40% Junior, 40% Mid, 20% Senior\n",
                        "Departments: 50% Finance, 30% IT, 20% HR\n",
                        "Turnover: 20% Left, 80% Stayed\n",
                        "Performance Score: Mean 70, SD 10",
                        "Tenure: 0-30 years")

#PLOT PREDICTIVE ANALYSIS FOR GENDER, JOB LEVEL & DEPARTMENT#

# Create a bar chart with corporate-friendly design and smaller axis titles
bar_chart <- ggplot(summary_data, aes(x = interaction(Gender, JobLevel, Department), y = AverageTurnoverProb, fill = Gender)) +
  geom_bar(stat = "identity", position = position_dodge(), color = "black", size = 0.1) +
  scale_fill_manual(values = c("Male" = "#1B4F72", "Female" = "#2874A6")) +
  labs(title = "Average Turnover Probability by Gender, Job Level, and Department", x = "Category", y = "Average Turnover Probability") +
  theme_minimal(base_size = 13, base_family = "Arial") +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 80, hjust = 1, color = "black", size = 8),
        axis.text.y = element_text(color = "black", size = 8),
        plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5, face = "bold", size = 12),
        legend.title = element_blank(),
        legend.position = "top",
        axis.title.x = element_text(size = 10),
        axis.title.y = element_text(size = 10))

SOCIAL NETWORKING

library(igraph)
## 
## Attaching package: 'igraph'
## The following objects are masked from 'package:dplyr':
## 
##     as_data_frame, groups, union
## The following objects are masked from 'package:stats':
## 
##     decompose, spectrum
## The following object is masked from 'package:base':
## 
##     union
library(dplyr)
library(ggplot2)

# Define the number of interactions
set.seed(123)
num_interactions <- 1000

# Generate random pairs of interactions among employees
interaction_pairs <- data.frame(
  Employee1 = sample(1:n, num_interactions, replace = TRUE),
  Employee2 = sample(1:n, num_interactions, replace = TRUE)
)

# Remove self-interactions
interaction_pairs <- interaction_pairs %>% filter(Employee1 != Employee2)

# Merge with employee data to add department information
interaction_pairs <- interaction_pairs %>%
  left_join(employee_data, by = c("Employee1" = "EmployeeID")) %>%
  rename(Department1 = Department) %>%
  left_join(employee_data, by = c("Employee2" = "EmployeeID")) %>%
  rename(Department2 = Department)

# Filter interactions within the same department
interaction_pairs <- interaction_pairs %>% filter(Department1 == Department2)

# Create a function to plot network for a specific department
plot_department_network <- function(department_name) {
  # Filter interactions for the department
  dept_interactions <- interaction_pairs %>% filter(Department1 == department_name)
  
  # Create a graph object
  g <- graph_from_data_frame(dept_interactions[, c("Employee1", "Employee2")], directed = FALSE)
  
  # Add attributes to vertices
  V(g)$Gender <- employee_data$Gender[as.integer(V(g)$name)]
  V(g)$JobLevel <- employee_data$JobLevel[as.integer(V(g)$name)]
  V(g)$Ethnicity <- employee_data$Ethnicity[as.integer(V(g)$name)]
  
  # Set color based on gender
  V(g)$color <- ifelse(V(g)$Gender == "Male", "#1B4F72", "#FF69B4")  # Blue for Male, Pink for Female
  
  # Set shape based on job level, using accepted shapes
  V(g)$shape <- ifelse(V(g)$JobLevel == "Junior", "circle", 
                       ifelse(V(g)$JobLevel == "Mid", "square", 
                              ifelse(V(g)$JobLevel == "Senior", "vrectangle", "circle")))
  
  # Plot the network
  plot(g, vertex.size = 5, vertex.label = NA, edge.arrow.size = 0.5,
       main = paste("Social Network for", department_name, "Department"),
       vertex.color = V(g)$color, vertex.shape = V(g)$shape)
  
  # Add legend for gender
  legend("topright", legend = c("Male", "Female"), col = c("#1B4F72", "#FF69B4"), pch = 16)
  
  # Manually add legend for job levels with correct shapes
  legend("bottomright", legend = c("Junior", "Mid", "Senior"), 
         col = "black", pch = c(21, 22, 15), pt.cex = 1.5, pt.bg = "black")
}

# Plot networks for each department
departments <- unique(employee_data$Department)
par(mfrow = c(1, length(departments))) # Adjust the layout based on the number of departments

for (dept in departments) {
  plot_department_network(dept)
}

# Reset layout
par(mfrow = c(1, 1))

# Plot the networks again individually for better visibility
for (dept in departments) {
  plot_department_network(dept)
}

# Function to compute and print centrality measures
compute_centrality <- function(department_name) {
  dept_interactions <- interaction_pairs %>% filter(Department1 == department_name)
  g <- graph_from_data_frame(dept_interactions[, c("Employee1", "Employee2")], directed = FALSE)
  
  # Compute centrality measures
  centrality <- data.frame(
    EmployeeID = as.integer(V(g)$name),  # Convert to integer for merging
    Degree = degree(g),
    Betweenness = betweenness(g),
    Closeness = closeness(g)
  )
  
  # Merge with employee_data
  centrality <- centrality %>%
    left_join(employee_data, by = "EmployeeID") %>%
    arrange(desc(Degree))
  
  # Print top 5 central employees in the department
  print(paste("Top 5 Central Employees in", department_name, "Department"))
  print(head(centrality, 5))
}

# Compute and print centrality measures for each department
for (dept in departments) {
  compute_centrality(dept)
}
